Et stipulandi et promittendi duo pluresve rei lieri possunt. stipulandi ita, si post omnium interrogationem promissor respondeat ‘spondeo' ut puta cum duobus separatim stipu- lantibus ita promissor respondeat ‘utrique vestrum dare sponde0:' nam si prius Titio spoponderit, deinde alio in· terrogante spondeat, alia atque alia erit obligatio nec creduntur

in iaciendo consistunt? The advantage oi the course recommended in the text was twofold. The promisee was saved the trouble of proving ‘quid sua intersit' (‘plerumque difficilis probatio est, quanti cuiusque intersit, et ad exiguam summam deducitur' Dig. 46. 5. 11); and if the contract came to be sued upon, the ground ol action was not the promise to do, but the promise to pay so much in desault, so that the remedy, instead of being the actio ex stipulatu, was condictio certi with its penal sponsio oi one third oi the sum in dispute: ‘cum quis non adiecerit poenam. . . incerti agendum esse' Dig. a. 5. 3. If no interval was fixed sor the performance oi an act secured by a penalty, the latter could be sued ior unless the act was performed within a reasonable time: ‘intra quantum autem temporis, nisi detur quod arbiter iusserit, committatur stipulatio, videndum est, et si quidem dies adiectus non sit, Celsus scribit libro ἰίο Digestorum inesse quoddam modicum tempus: quod ubi praeterierit, poena statim peti potest’ Dig. 4. 8. 21. 12. The amount os the poena had no measure except the will of the parties, and it might be recovered in full, even though largely exceeding the value of the act or forbearance stipulated lor, Dig. 4 8. 32· pr.; 21. 2. 56.
